<Article
  title="The Most Common Ways Co-op Teams Wipe (And How to Prevent Them)"
  description="Most team wipes aren’t because someone is bad at the game. They’re caused by predictable communication failures and bad habits. Here’s what we see constantly and how to stop it."
  kicker="Team Pitfalls"
  date="2026-06-25"
  heading="Common Co-op Mistakes"
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="sec">
    <p>After watching hundreds of runs (and dying in many of them ourselves), a clear pattern emerges: the deadliest mistakes are almost always the same few things repeated.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>1. “Just one more item” syndrome</h2>
    <p>The quota is already met. Everyone is heading to the exit. Then one person says “wait, there’s a big piece over there” and the whole squad gets wiped trying to recover the body.</p>
    <p><strong>Fix:</strong> Agree on a hard “extract when quota is reached” rule before the run. Make it non-negotiable.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>2. Vague callouts</h2>
    <p>“There’s something behind me.” This tells your teammates almost nothing useful.</p>
    <p>Good callouts include: type of threat + distance/direction + what you’re doing + what you need.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>3. No one wants to be the “fun police”</h2>
    <p>When the whole team is looting happily, the first person to say “we should leave” feels like a buzzkill.</p>
    <p><strong>Fix:</strong> Rotate an official “Abort Authority” role every run. Everyone agrees in advance to respect the call.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>4. Solo heroics</h2>
    <p>“I’ll just check that room real quick.” Five minutes later the team is searching for a body in the dark.</p>
    <p><strong>Fix:</strong> Buddy system by default. Only split when you have explicit roles and check-in times.</p>
  </section>
</Article>
